entry.title: Stop the blocking request for policy after the session is stopping
entry.content:
Sending a blocking D-Bus request after the session is stopping can

cause a dead-lock where session_manager is waiting for Chrome and

Chrome is waiting for response from D-Bus.



In this CL we subscribe to the signal to get when the session is

stopping and stop sending the blocking requests after that.



For now only requests to for the device policy is blocked

and if this will bring results, a follow up CL will stop sending

all other blocking requests.



BUG=1477697, 1475979, 836388

TEST=Manual test on device

entry.title: Remove {On/Did}StartLoadingResponseBody()
entry.content:
Currently when MojoURLLoaderClient::OnReceiveResponse() receives the

response, it calls two methods OnReceivedResponse() and

OnStartLoadingResponseBody().



Before this CL:

- MojoURLLoaderClient::OnReceiveResponse()

- ResourceRequestSender::OnReceivedResponse()

- URLLoader::Context::OnReceivedResponse()

- ResourceLoader::DidReceiveResponse()

- ResourceRequestSender::OnStartLoadingResponseBody()

- URLLoader::Context::OnStartLoadingResponseBody()

- ResourceLoader::DidStartLoadingResponseBody()



After this CL:

- MojoURLLoaderClient::OnReceiveResponse()

- ResourceRequestSender::OnReceivedResponse()

- URLLoader::Context::OnReceivedResponse()

- ResourceLoader::DidReceiveResponse()



There is a historical reason that the renderer process received the

response and the body in two IPCs (OnReceiveResponse,

OnStartLoadingResponseBody). But now they have been merged by

https://crrev.com/c/3410912. So we don't need to keep two methods.



Bug: 1379780

entry.title: Skip OnAppUpdate if there is no change for the published apps.
entry.content:
When the AppStorage is enabled, the apps could be published twice by

AppStorage and publishers with the same app info. For example:

1. Read AppStorage, and publish the builtin apps.

2. Builtin apps publisher is created, and publish the builtin apps

again.

Then OnAppUpdate could be called twice as well.



This CL modifies AppRegistryCache, to compare delta and state. If there

is no change, don't call OnAppUpdate.



Set paused as false in AppStorage to keep the consistent implementation

as publishers, as that is the default init value in AppPublisher.



Clean up app_registry_cache_unittest to remove the tests added for the

non mojom work.

entry.title: Report full page process list in ReportPageProcessesPolicy
entry.content:
The page process list is sent to the resource manager daemon

(resourced). The page process list is used to estimate the memory usage

of the background and protected processes. Based on the Chrome memory

usage, resourced determines when to release memory from Chrome or VMs or

container. When there are a lot of background processes in Ash Chrome,

resourced avoids killing perceptible apps in VMs or container.



If the last page node event is within the miminum report interval, start

a timer to ensure the page process list is reported after the last page

node event.



Deprecate crosapi ReportBackgroundProcesses.

entry.title: Fix janky scrollbar animations.
entry.content:
There are certain scenarios that causes overlay scrollbars animations to

end abruptly. They are mostly caused by

ScrollbarAnimationController::UpdateScrollbarState calling

SingleScrollbarAnimationControllerThinning::UpdateThumbThicknessScale(),

which stops thinning animations indiscriminately.

These scenarios don't happen enough to be extremely noticeable and they

are not necessarily easy to reproduce, so they become easy to ignore.

For some example scenarios, please see the associated bug.



Changelist:

- UpdateScrollbarState() no longer calls the function that stops

thinning animations.

- The thinning controller functions will now decide when they want to

cancel the thinning animation.

- Fixed a DidMouseLeave Fluent-specific bug that caused animation stops,

now if you leave the scrollable area while thickening, the animation

will bounce back via a thinning animation.

where it checks the `encoder` pointer.



A change has been made to check for AV1 supportability with

hardware when ENABLE_LIBAOM is disabled.

entry.title: bruschetta: Enable security key forwarding on lacros
entry.content:
Currently messages for gnubbyd from the VM flow like this:



VM -> cicerone -> ash::VmSKForwardingServiceProvider

-> ash::guest_os::VmSKForwardingNativeMessageHost

-> forwarding extension -> gnubbyd



With this CL the flow is now:



VM -> cicerone -> ash::VmSKForwardingServiceProvider

-> guest_os::GuestOsSkForwarder

-> crosapi mojo link to lacros

-> guest_os::VmSkForwardingService

-> guest_os::VmSKForwardingNativeMessageHost

-> forwarding extension -> gnubbyd



Additionally, some plumbing is required to establish the mojo

connection. This flows in the opposite direction:



guest_os::VmSkForwardingService -> crosapi::GuestOsSkForwarderFactoryAsh

-> guest_os::GuestOsSkForwarder



To support both lacros-only and lacros-disabled,

guest_os::GuestOsSkForwarder will pass the message either to the old

code path or the new, depending on the lacros enabled state. This

unfortunately means the code in VmSKForwardingNativeMessageHost is

duplicated temporarily, but the copy in ash can be removed once running

without lacros is no longer supported.

entry.title: Add heartbeat mechanism to pixel tests
entry.content:
Adds a heartbeat mechanism similar to the one used by WebGL and WebGPU

tests to the pixel and expected_color suites. Like the WebGL

implementation, the actual test page is now loaded within an iframe

so that we can guarantee the websocket connection is set up before

testing begins.



In addition to having to shuffle around a fair bit of code, this ends

up requiring us to switch how non-standard test actions are handled

in the pixel tests. Previously, such actions were defined within the

suite itself. Now, each test case is capable of defining an arbitrary

list of test actions to perform in order between loading the test page

and capturing the screenshot for comparison. If not specified, the

harness defaults to waiting for the test page to signal that it is done,

which is equivalent to the default behavior before.

entry.title: IndexedDB: lazily recalculate usage for quota
entry.content:
Quota clients such as IndexedDB typically provide the quota manager

with an initial usage figure and later update it as needed via

`NotifyBucketModified` and a provided size delta, measured in bytes.

For IndexedDB, predicting changes in usage just by looking at

in-flight transactions is very hard, so after every operation that

potentially changes the usage, it re-queries the disk to

get the total size of the folders where it stores data (LevelDB files

and blobs). Somewhat backwardly, it then calculates a delta by

subtracting the old value from the new value, and passes that delta to

the quota manager. This is a very inefficient system because it reads

from disk quite often (e.g. after each one of 1000 sequential

transactions), and in so doing blocks queued IDB actions and

transactions.



It's apparent that the design of the quota manager-client

relationship was not conceived with IndexedDB in mind. This change

modifies the contract between client and manager such that clients

*may* opt to simply dirty the usage cache that's kept by the manager.

Instead of passing a delta in bytes, the client (in this case IDB)

passes a null value which indicates that the cache should be

discarded. It will defer actually recalculating the cache until

necessary, e.g. due to a call to `navigator.storage.estimate()` or

another storage API querying the manager for overall usage.



On the benchmark mentioned in the bug, this change performs

equivalently to the "dumb" solution of completely ignoring quota

because the benchmark never triggers a usage recalculation.



This change also makes the simple but useful improvement of skipping

all quota update logic upon completion of a readonly transaction.

entry.title: Fenced frames: Fix automatic beacon dev tool support
entry.content:
`SendFencedFrameReportingBeaconInternal` used to take an argument

`initiator_frame_tree_node_id`, used only for dev tools support. This

argument was set incorrectly for automatic beacons (target frame rather

than initiator frame). This CL fixes the bug by eliminating the argument

entirely; the function is always called on the initiator RFHI, so we can

just get the current FTN id inside the function.
